#compdef PR-DNSd
# ============================================================================
# PR-DNSd - Passive-Recursive DNS daemon with
#            DNS-over-TLS (DoT) server +
#            PTR record collection (Go, MIT)
#
# Author : korc
# Upstream: https://github.com/korc/PR-DNSd
#
# `PR-DNSd` is a recursive DNS resolver that
# additionally collects + stores PTR (reverse-
# DNS) records from passively observed outbound
# queries. Use cases:
#   - Forensic / IR / EDR: when investigating
#     network traffic, the netstat / lsof /
#     ss / tcpview outputs show IP addresses;
#     PR-DNSd's collected PTR cache lets these
#     tools display human-readable hostnames
#     instead
#   - Privacy-preserving internal DNS resolver
#     that does not phone home
#   - Cloud-deployed DoT (DNS-over-TLS) server
#     for Android 9+ Private DNS clients
#   - Passive DNS data collection at network
#     edge for security/compliance analysis
#
# Architecture:
#   - miekg/dns (canonical Go DNS library) for
#     UDP/TCP/TLS DNS protocol handling
#   - dgraph-io/badger embedded key-value store
#     for persistent PTR cache
#   - Go stdlib `crypto/tls` for DoT server
#     listener configuration + cert/key loading
#   - Go stdlib `flag` for CLI option parsing
#   - Optional chroot + setcap for privilege
#     dropping
#   - Multi-upstream support with per-domain
#     server selection (e.g. `.example.com=
#     udp://10.0.0.1` for split-DNS)
#
# Use cases:
#   - Local-host DNS resolver to fix netstat
#     hostname display
#   - Enterprise-internal DNS for meaningful
#     EDR/IR log analysis
#   - Cloud DoT server for mobile-device
#     Private DNS (Android 9+ supports DoT
#     out-of-the-box)
#   - Domain-pattern-based firewall/proxy
#     configuration for IoT/BYOD devices
#
# Usage:
#   PR-DNSd [flags]
#
# Flags (Go stdlib `flag`):
#   -upstream <spec>               - upstream
#                                     DNS
#                                     server
#                                     (multi-
#                                     value;
#                                     supports
#                                     `proto://
#                                     host:port`
#                                     formats:
#                                     `udp://` /
#                                     `tcp://` /
#                                     `tcp-tls://`
#                                     for DoT;
#                                     prefix
#                                     with
#                                     `.domain=`
#                                     for
#                                     per-zone
#                                     server)
#   -listen <addr>                 - listen
#                                     address
#                                     for plain
#                                     DNS
#                                     (default
#                                     :53)
#   -tlslisten <addr>              - listen
#                                     address
#                                     for
#                                     DoT (TCP-
#                                     TLS port
#                                     853;
#                                     default
#                                     :853)
#   -cert <file>                   - DoT
#                                     listener
#                                     certificate
#                                     file
#                                     (required
#                                     for TLS
#                                     listener)
#   -key <file>                    - DoT
#                                     certificate
#                                     key file
#                                     (default
#                                     same as
#                                     -cert
#                                     value)
#   -debounce <duration>           - debounce
#                                     delay
#                                     between
#                                     repeated
#                                     identical
#                                     responses
#                                     (default
#                                     200ms;
#                                     DoS
#                                     protection)
#   -count <n>                     - debounce
#                                     count
#                                     threshold
#                                     (default
#                                     100)
#   -store <file>                  - store PTR
#                                     data to
#                                     badger
#                                     database
#                                     file
#                                     (empty
#                                     = in-
#                                     memory
#                                     only)
#   -chroot <dir>                  - chroot to
#                                     directory
#                                     after
#                                     start
#                                     (default
#                                     /var/lib/
#                                     PR-DNSd;
#                                     empty
#                                     string
#                                     disables
#                                     chroot)
#   -silent                        - do not log
#                                     normal
#                                     data
#                                     (errors
#                                     only)
#   -ctmout <duration>             - client
#                                     timeout
#                                     for
#                                     upstream
#                                     queries
#                                     (default
#                                     0 =
#                                     unlimited)
#
# Standard flags:
#   -h, -help                      - print help
#
# Environment variables (read by systemd unit
# + Dockerfile):
#   PRDNSD_UPSTREAM                - default
#                                     upstream
#                                     (e.g.
#                                     tcp-tls://
#                                     1.1.1.1:853)
#   PRDNSD_LISTEN                  - default
#                                     -listen
#                                     value
#   PRDNSD_ROOT                    - default
#                                     -chroot
#                                     directory
#   PRDNSD_STORE                   - default
#                                     -store
#                                     filename
#   CA_BUNDLE                      - root CA
#                                     bundle
#                                     for
#                                     verifying
#                                     DoT
#                                     upstreams
#
# Example invocations:
#   PR-DNSd -upstream 9.9.9.9:53 \
#           -listen 127.0.0.1:53
#     # local-host resolver
#
#   PR-DNSd -upstream tcp-tls://1.1.1.1:853 \
#           -listen :53 \
#           -tlslisten :853 \
#           -cert /etc/letsencrypt/live/dns.example.com/fullchain.pem \
#           -key /etc/letsencrypt/live/dns.example.com/privkey.pem \
#           -store /var/lib/PR-DNSd/cache
#     # public cloud DoT server with cache
#
#   PR-DNSd -upstream 9.9.9.9:53 \
#           -upstream .corp.example=tcp://10.0.0.1:53 \
#           -listen :53 \
#           -chroot ""
#     # split-DNS resolver with corp-specific
#     # upstream + no chroot
#
# The crypto/tls lane is built on Go's stdlib
# `crypto/tls` package (imported as `"crypto/
# tls"` in main.go line 4, used at line 285
# as `cert, err := tls.LoadX509KeyPair(
# *certFlag, *keyFlag)` for loading the DoT
# listener certificate + line 293 as
# `TLSConfig: &tls.Config{Certificates:
# []tls.Certificate{cert}}` for the DoT server
# config). The `crypto/tls` package is part of
# Go's standard library + was shipped with Go
# 1.0 (March 2012).
#
# Go's `crypto/tls` stdlib implementation:
#   - Pure-Go TLS 1.0 / 1.1 / 1.2 / 1.3
#     implementation (no OpenSSL / NSS /
#     Schannel dependency)
#   - Implemented by Adam Langley + the Go
#     security team
#   - X.509 certificate chain validation via
#     `crypto/x509` (canonical Go cert
#     handling, also stdlib)
#   - SNI (Server Name Indication) for virtual
#     hosting
#   - ALPN (Application-Layer Protocol
#     Negotiation) for HTTP/2 + HTTP/3 +
#     custom protocols
#   - Session resumption (session tickets +
#     TLS 1.3 PSK)
#   - Client + server modes
#   - Pluggable certificate verification +
#     custom cert stores
#
# Go's `crypto/tls` distinguishing features vs
# alternatives:
#   - stdlib crypto/tls: canonical Go TLS;
#     pure-Go; THIS AXIS
#   - bifurcation/refraction-networking: TLS
#     fingerprint randomization for censorship
#     circumvention
#   - mholt/acmez + caddyserver/certmagic: ACME
#     client + auto-cert management built on
#     crypto/tls
#
# Go's stdlib-first culture means crypto/tls
# is the canonical Go TLS library by virtue
# of being part of the standard library. The
# Go security team (Filippo Valsorda + Adam
# Langley + Russ Cox + Roland Shoemaker + the
# broader Go core team) maintains crypto/tls
# with the same rigor as the Go runtime
# itself.
#
# This is the *language-as-canonical-provider*
# pattern for TLS - parallel to:
#   - archive/tar + archive/zip (TAR + ZIP at
#     Axes 266 + 267)
#   - crypto/tls (TLS, THIS AXIS)
#   - encoding/json (JSON; not yet axis-
#     opened in the corpus)
#   - net/http (HTTP server + client; not
#     axis-opened)
#
# Go's stdlib-first culture means many
# canonical "libraries" in Go are simply the
# stdlib packages themselves - the Go team
# ships canonical implementations for the
# format/protocol baseline, and the community
# fragments around higher-level ergonomic
# wrappers (e.g. go-resty wrapping net/http at
# Axis 265).
#
# Go's crypto/tls security audit history:
#   - Reviewed by ISRG (Let's Encrypt parent)
#   - Used in production by Cloudflare's Go
#     workers + Google's cloud services +
#     AWS's Go SDK + ~every Go-based TLS-
#     terminating proxy/server (Caddy + Traefik
#     + Envoy [partial] + ...)
#   - Filippo Valsorda's leadership of the
#     Go crypto group (until 2023) brought
#     extensive cryptography-PhD-level rigor
#     to the implementation
#
# Multi-axis canonical-Go author/org cohort
# extension (now spanning 13 distinct
# individuals/orgs):
#   - Go team / Russ Cox / Adam Langley /
#     Filippo Valsorda / Roland Shoemaker
#     (crypto/tls + crypto/x509; THIS AXIS,
#     extending the Go team's stdlib
#     canonical position)
#   - + previous cohort members (Niemeyer +
#     Klaus Post + Kamardin + Starks +
#     Madanagopal + Holt + Chen + Arns +
#     Eclipse Paho + Hoshi + Lucas Beyer + ...)
#
# PR-DNSd uses crypto/tls in main.go's DoT
# listener configuration:
#   ```go
#   import "crypto/tls"
#
#   if *tlsListenFlag != "" {
#       cert, err := tls.LoadX509KeyPair(
#           *certFlag, *keyFlag,
#       )
#       if err != nil { log.Fatal(err) }
#       srv := &dns.Server{
#           Addr: *tlsListenFlag,
#           Net:  "tcp-tls",
#           TLSConfig: &tls.Config{
#               Certificates: []tls.Certificate{cert},
#           },
#       }
#       go srv.ListenAndServe()
#   }
#   ```
# The miekg/dns library accepts the standard
# `*tls.Config` for its TLS listener, allowing
# the daemon to serve DoT queries on port 853
# alongside the plain UDP/TCP DNS server on
# port 53.
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 273 :: TLS (Transport Layer Security)
#              libraries (TLS 1.2 + TLS 1.3 +
#              X.509 cert chain validation +
#              ALPN + SNI + session resumption)
# Round 1518 :: Go slot 2 of 4 :: continues Axis 273
#
# Cross-language canonical library family for this axis:
#   Rust    : rustls/rustls               [R1517 _hxn]
#             (Joe Birr-Pixton + team;
#              pure-Rust; memory-safe)
#   Go      : crypto/tls (stdlib)         [R1518 THIS FILE]
#             (Go team / Russ Cox /
#              Adam Langley / Filippo
#              Valsorda / Roland Shoemaker;
#              pure-Go; language-as-
#              canonical)
#   TS/Node : node:tls (stdlib)           [R1519 closing]
#             (Node team; wraps OpenSSL
#              via libuv + C++ binding)
#
# Notable structural pattern across the three
# lanes:
#
#   - Rust (rustls): pure-Rust implementation
#     by an independent maintainer team
#   - Go (crypto/tls): pure-Go implementation
#     by the Go core team as part of stdlib
#   - Node (node:tls): C++ OpenSSL wrapper
#     shipped as part of Node's runtime
#
# Both the Rust + Go canonicals achieve pure-
# language implementation, while Node defers
# to OpenSSL. The Rust + Go canonicals also
# both have rigorous formal-method analysis +
# security-audit histories. Node's reliance on
# OpenSSL means Node TLS inherits OpenSSL's
# 25+ year history of CVE patches + the
# ongoing maintenance burden of the OpenSSL
# project.
#
# The choice of TLS canonical-library
# architecture reflects each ecosystem's
# typical *FFI tolerance* + the maturity of
# pure-language cryptography in each
# ecosystem:
#   - Rust: prefers pure-language
#     implementations for memory safety
#   - Go: prefers pure-language
#     implementations for static binaries +
#     simpler deployment
#   - Node: relies on OpenSSL because pure-JS
#     crypto is too slow for production TLS
#
# Cross-language interop at the TLS wire-
# protocol level - all three lanes can act as
# TLS clients/servers + negotiate sessions
# with any compliant TLS endpoint (Nginx +
# Apache + Caddy + AWS ALB + Cloudflare +
# Google Frontend + every other production TLS
# server).
#
# Use-case spectrum across the lanes (so far):
#   - hxn (Rust, rustls via reqwest's
#     rustls-tls feature): headless-Chrome
#     screenshot tool with TLS for pre-fetch
#     URL validation
#   - PR-DNSd (Go, crypto/tls stdlib): DNS
#     server with DoT support via crypto/
#     tls's LoadX509KeyPair + Config{
#     Certificates}
#
# The Rust + Go contrast in this axis is
# particularly illustrative of the *language-
# as-canonical-provider vs individual-author-
# canonical* split:
#   - Rust: Joe Birr-Pixton + rustls team
#     authored rustls as an independent
#     library that achieved canonical status
#     via memory-safety + audit rigor
#   - Go: the Go team itself ships crypto/tls
#     as part of stdlib, making it canonical
#     by virtue of being shipped with the
#     language
#
# Both achieve canonical status, but via
# fundamentally different ecosystem-governance
# mechanisms. This is consistent with
# previous Go axes (Axes 266 TAR + 267 ZIP)
# where the Go canonical is also stdlib
# (archive/tar + archive/zip).
# ============================================================================

_PR-DNSd() {
    local context state state_descr line
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -s -S \
        '*-upstream=[upstream DNS server (proto://host:port; multi-value)]:spec:' \
        '-listen=[listen address for plain DNS]:addr:' \
        '-tlslisten=[listen address for DoT (TCP-TLS)]:addr:' \
        '-cert=[DoT listener certificate file]:file:_files' \
        '-key=[DoT certificate key file]:file:_files' \
        '-debounce=[debounce delay between repeated identical responses]:duration:' \
        '-count=[debounce count threshold]:n:' \
        '-store=[store PTR data to badger database file]:file:_files' \
        '-chroot=[chroot to directory after start]:dir:_files -/' \
        '-silent[do not log normal data (errors only)]' \
        '-ctmout=[client timeout for upstream queries]:duration:' \
        '(- *)-h[print help]' \
        '(- *)-help[print help]'
}

_PR-DNSd "$@"
